		  . The fact that Henry’s mother had not seen him for several years did not in my judgment absolve the authority of the responsibility of satisfying the important statutory requirement to establish whether she was, for example, “willing and able” to “provide accommodation” for him or “arrange for accommodation to be provided” for him; nor could the Local Authority say that it had complied with its obligation under section 22C(2)-(4) CA 1989, namely the requirement to make arrangements for Henry to live with a parent, except where it would not be consistent with his welfare.  The statute is clear enough; the guidance reinforces it: “A local authority cannot restrict a person’s exercise of their PR, including their decisions about delegation, unless there is a care order or an emergency protection order in place.” (The Children Act 1989 Guidance and Regulations, Volume 2: Care Planning, Placement and Case Review, para 3.197 (DfE, 2015);

